This morning, while performing routine maintenance, West Texas Gas (WTG) experienced an unintended release of mercaptan odorant from a bulk holding tank at one of our San Antonio facilities. The release was not the result of a natural gas leak, but of a mercaptan odorant mixture commonly used to odorize natural gas to give it a distinctive odor for safety purposes.



As a result, the odor may be noticeable across parts of the San Antonio area. The vicinity is safe and there is no danger to the public and there was no natural gas released during the incident.

Miles Collins

@Hensel, Dillon<mailto:DHensel@westtexasgas.com> Below is the statement being released. It can be referenced if you receive any calls.



@Miles Collins<mailto:MCollins@westtexasgas.com>,



This is the statement we want added to the homepage:



This morning, while performing routine maintenance, West Texas Gas (WTG) experienced an unintended release of mercaptan odorant from a bulk holding tank at one of our San Antonio facilities. The release was not the result of a natural gas leak, but of a mercaptan odorant mixture commonly used to odorize natural gas to give it a distinctive odor for safety purposes.



As a result, the odor may be noticeable across parts of the San Antonio area. The vicinity is safe and there is no danger to the public and there was no natural gas released during the incident.



If you suspect a natural gas leak in your area, we urge you to contact your local utility provider or call 911 out of an abundance of caution.



We will continue to monitor the situation and provide updates as needed.





Matthew Smith

P: 432-253-4633

We’re leveraging a new tool to centrally manage email signatures for WTG which will enable us to standardize signatures across the company centrally and easily. Will these new signatures sync to my mobile device? Yes. This tool will deploy the plugin to your iPhone Outlook and keep your mobile emails in compliance with the standard signatures.

When will everyone else get this new signature? We’re working on cleaning up the end user data for field sites and will deploy those in the next two weeks.

Thanks Diana, this list looks awesome!  Two things that would be great for next steps:



  *   Add LinkedIn profiles hyperlinks for those you can find here and put NA if you can’t find on LinkedIn.
  *   Let’s add Google, Amazon, IBM, Akamai, Cisco, Digital Ocean to our list.
  *   Get a subscription to RocketReach<https://rocketreach.co/> and ZoomInfo<https://www.zoominfo.com/data>



My AI search for other possible contact databases provided the below results:

Top 5 Companies

Here’s a breakdown of each, highlighting why they’re suitable for your needs:

  *   ZoomInfo: A leader in B2B contact data, offering names, phone numbers, emails, and social media profiles. It has global coverage but some users report occasional data quality issues.
  *   RocketReach: Known for verified contact information, including emails and phone numbers, with a large database. However, data accuracy can be inconsistent.
  *   UpLead: Claims high data accuracy (95%) with over 160 million organizations and 300 million contacts, plus real-time email verification. It’s great for targeted outreach.
  *   Cognism: Focuses on accurate, compliant data with phone-verified mobile numbers and business emails, covering North America, Europe, and Asia-Pacific. It’s reliable for GDPR compliance.
  *   Apollo.io: Offers a large database (210 million contacts, 35 million companies) with sales engagement tools, though some data may be outdated.

Pricing and Considerations

All these services are subscription-based, with pricing varying by features and usage. For example, ZoomInfo starts at around $14,995/year, RocketReach at $32/month, UpLead at $99/month, Cognism has customized pricing, and Apollo.io starts at $49/month. Choose based on your budget and the accuracy you need, as data quality can vary.





Charlie Beecherl

{"from": {"emailAddress": {"name": "Corey Ward", "address": "cward@westtexasgas.com"}}, "sender": {"name": "Corey Ward", "address": "cward@westtexasgas.com"}, "content": "Miles – we tweaked the language a little – see below. Could we add on the website “SAN ANTONIO AREA ALERT” before the statement?



This morning, while performing routine maintenance, West Texas Gas (WTG) experienced an unintended release of mercaptan odorant from a bulk holding tank at one of our San Antonio facilities. The release was not the result of a natural gas leak, but of a mercaptan odorant mixture commonly used to odorize natural gas to give it a distinctive odor for safety purposes.

The vicinity was deemed safe and no natural gas was released during the incident. However, the odor may be noticeable across parts of the San Antonio into the evening. If you suspect a natural gas leak in your area, we urge you to contact your local utility provider or call 911 out of an abundance of caution.

We will continue to monitor the situation and provide updates as needed.


Corey Ward

@Hensel, Dillon<mailto:DHensel@westtexasgas.com> Below is the statement being released. It can be referenced if you receive any calls.

This is the statement we want added to the homepage:



This morning, while performing routine maintenance, West Texas Gas (WTG) experienced an unintended release of mercaptan odorant from a bulk holding tank at one of our San Antonio facilities. The release was not the result of a natural gas leak, but of a mercaptan odorant mixture commonly used to odorize natural gas to give it a distinctive odor for safety purposes.



As a result, the odor may be noticeable across parts of the San Antonio area. The vicinity is safe and there is no danger to the public and there was no natural gas released during the incident.



If you suspect a natural gas leak in your area, we urge you to contact your local utility provider or call 911 out of an abundance of caution.



We will continue to monitor the situation and provide updates as needed.





Matthew Smith

What is this change? At some point Tuesday, you’ll notice your default signature for new emails and replies change to style & format below. There is no action required on your part.

  *
West Texas Gas Utility
  *
WTG Gas Transmission
  *
WTG Gas Marketing
  *
Western Gas Interstate

WTG Bexar County is a newly formed entity and is expected to have similar accounting activity to the other subsidiaries within the next few months
The CIS will be housed within West Texas Gas Utility.
WTG Operator serves as the paymaster, handling payroll and benefits for all employees. These costs are then allocated across the subsidiaries.
Shared expenses are processed through WTG Downstream Holdings and subsequently re-billed to the appropriate subsidiaries, either based on predetermined allocation formulas or actual usage.
I’ll follow up with separate emails containing examples related to rebill allocations, payroll recharges, consolidations, affiliates, and other relevant items.

All,



The current domain owner of wtgenergy.com has responded to our inquiry and is interested in selling the domain.

The sell countered my initial offer of $1,000-$3,500 with $45,000-$55,000.



Our broker has suggested we counter with $30,000-$35,000 to see how firm they are on this specific range.



Given how important a good domain is to our rebranding, where does everyone stand on proceeding with this next counter range in effort to secure the domain?

Based on the decision made today I have begun work to procure wtgenergy.com. It is currently owned by a third party, but not in use. I’ve engaged a broker to help us contact the owner and work through procuring it.



I will keep you all posted as I progress through this process.



Excited for this next chapter!

raw_content:
{"from": {"emailAddress": {"name": "Reed, Andy", "address": "AReed@westtexasgas.com"}}, "sender": {"name": "Reed, Andy", "address": "AReed@westtexasgas.com"}, "content": "Kent/Reid - Attached is an example of a payroll download from Paycom, along with a walkthrough of how the rebill process is currently managed primarily through Excel. Included are the following:


  *
WTGO 06.18.25 – This is the cash payment journal entry for a routine bi-weekly payroll run exported from Paycom.
Employees in Paycom are tagged with an identifier indicating either:

        a) 100% rebill to a specific subsidiary, or
        b) Allocation based on predefined percentages (reset annually).
    These allocations fall into two categories:

     *
1092 Allocated G&A – e.g., Finance, CEO, etc.
     *
1092 Allocated Opex – e.g., Safety, Environmental, etc.
  *
Downstream Payroll Expense Worksheet – Summarizes GL-level payroll expense details by subsidiary for rebilling purposes.
  *
Downstream Payroll Rebill – Takes the output from the above worksheet and formats it into a rebill invoice. Each subsidiary records this invoice as a payroll accrual entry and processes it through accounts payable like any other vendor invoice.

One area that could be improved would be the ability to post both sides of the entry. For example, WTG Operator and the respective subsidiary within the system. Currently, the reliance on Excel for this step creates manual work and opportunities for error.
Amanda, please feel free to correct or clarify anything I may have misstated.

  *


[WTG Logo_small.png]

 Andy Reed

 Vice President and Chief Accounting Officer

 O: 432-253-4613

 AReed@westtexasgas.com


", "recipients": [{"emailAddress": {"name": "Kent Landrum", "address": "KLandrum@opportune.com"}}, {"emailAddress": {"name": "Reid Rorick", "address": "RRorick@opportune.com"}}]}
subject: Payroll Rebill Process Overview and Paycom Download Example
